segments.text: The boys that lived in the house begged me to paddle them and I didn't paddle them because I didn't, they wanted to be able to say how much that they got, how much they suffered when they didn't suffer at all.
But I was so annoyed about the hazing that I
wouldn't use the board, and other than that, there was no hazing in the project houses.
One of the students that was in the Lufkin house where I moved was a fellow by the name of Starr, and I was quite, and if you read my memoirs,
get a lot of information about my relationship with the Starr family.
I don't want to recount that now.
And by then you were beginning to decide about being a dairy science major?
That's right.
Describe the routine of courses for a dairy science major.
Well, in general, they were the same courses that all agriculture students took.
There was not much difference.
But my senior year, I decided that the prospects of getting a job in dairy field management, there was jobs available for dairy ice cream
Production people, but not for herd work.
And so I took 20 hours.
And in addition, I audited four hours because I needed the course to have a double major.
I was in class every hour in the week.
And I was living in the dorm.
but I was in class every hour in the week except religious emphasis week.
And because of my heavy load, I was a distinguished student my senior year.
A's count so much and B's count so much and I probably, I probably had a
1.7 or 9 or something.
I really did not have a B average, and yet I was a distinguished student because I'd taken such a heavy load.
Who were the key dairy science instructors in those days?
Dean.
Kyle?
No, Shepard, who later became a Federal Reserve man, was an instructor.
And Darnell was the dairy cattle judge coach.
And I really didn't know anybody other than those two people.
If you needed advice in those days about what courses to take or what to do, where did you go to seek advice and counsel?
I don't know how to answer that question.
It was just like this poll in the audience.
But did Dan Russell, was he a person that would say, here's what you ought to do?
No.
We had no contact with him except as a supervisor.
Go ahead.
Were there nicknames for faculty members and students in those days?
Yes, sir.
What was yours?
I never knew.
I never knew.
What were some that you remember for faculty?
Head N. Jones was one of them in the chemistry.
I don't remember.
Did Dr. Russell have one yet?
I didn't know it if he did.
Because when I got there, he was Dr. Dan the grade point man.
Supposedly that he would pass you if you would give any effort.
By the way, what year did you get there?
Same year Mr. Rutter got there a few months before I did.
Is that right?
Yes, sir.
I always thought that they made a mistake when they let the Rutter preceding man
Morgan?
Right.
I thought he was one of the more capable.
He had the same ideas that later would become...
I understand.
Let's see.
Describe the dormitory...
When you lived in the dormitory on the campus, describe the routine of life in that dormitory.
Well...
Since they had two rooms of seniors, four people, and I was the fifth one, they put me in the same room with the first sergeant of the company.
And I'd get up in time to get to the mess hall.
And by the time I got through eating after serving the meals,
I was on my way to class.
I generally didn't have to go back to my room.
And incidentally, 50 years after the fact, I found that my orderly was one of my competitors.
compadres in the China, Burma, India campaign.
He's a little older than I am.
And I've recently contacted him and we've had dinner together.
He's a little older than I am.
Your task in the dining hall, what was your job there?
I carried the trays.
So you would report for breakfast at about what time?
I don't remember exactly.
But I had to be there ready to dish the food out
They did give me one.
They gave me the first table out of the door so I didn't have to carry the food to the far end.
The freshmen did.
But the people on my table were the staff of A&M.
The cadet colonel and the lieutenant colonel and all of the staff officers.
The big shots of that senior class were at the table I waited on.
And how were you treated as a waiter by those people?
No different than they would have treated any other person.
Then you would eat quickly and head off to class for an 8 o'clock.
That's right.
Then you'd come back to begin your lunch assignment.
As soon as I finished my 12 o'clock class.
And I'd eat quickly and go to my 1 o'clock class my senior year.
And then the same for supper.
What time would you get through in the evening?
I imagine 7, 7.15, something like that.
And what dormitory did you live in that year?
Ross Hall.
Ross Hall.
Describe it.
Well, it was one of the oldest dormitories on the campus.
And the latrine was on the bottom floor, and they finally installed a urinal on the third floor.
And the rooms were fairly big enough as far as I'm concerned.
And I sort of made it known that I didn't care what time my roommate came in at night.
But he wasn't to come in and wake me up because he was drunk.
And I made that, you know, I just leave it at that.
I never went in hard.
Hard.
Hard haul?
No.
I'm talking about the very joint.
Oh, hard liquors.
Hard liquors.
Hard liquors.
I never went in hard liquors while I was there.
Now, it was.
south on Welborn Road, south of the campus.
That's right.
Where else, other than that, did Aggies drink beer?
I don't know.
Because to get whiskey, they had to go towards Snook, cross Whiskey Bridge.
There was no place in downtown.
I've never heard of a bootlegger in the county.
No.
When, on Saturday night, if you and some of your friends wanted to have a good time, where did y'all go?
We went to a dormitory room and played bridge.
I played bridge on Saturday night many, many times.
No poker?
No poker.
I never played poker.
Always bridge.
It was a hard job to find four people to play bridge with on Saturday night.
And how long did those bridge games sometimes last?
Oh, till midnight.
Okay.
Then on Sunday afternoon, what did y'all do?
I don't know how to answer that question.
I just don't remember.
What about, did you go to the clay pits?
No.
I spent my Sunday afternoon...
on religious work, visiting students that I could find in their rooms.
What about some good bull pranks and jokes that you remember that happened?
What were some of the pranks that students played on somebody, whether you were involved or not?
Well, Float Out, I guess you've heard of that, haven't you?
pouring water on somebody from an upper story.
I really don't have much comment on that.
Did you go to any of the dances?
No.
Did you not believe in dancing or just didn't go?
Well, I didn't go because I couldn't dance and I
my religious faith was such that I probably would not have gone.
I've never danced as far as that's concerned.
Describe a football weekend in those years.
Well, I had to go on the court trips, but I didn't have enough money to buy a ticket.
And I'd stand at the gate till the half when they opened the gate and I'd go in.
But one of the most lonesome trips I ever made was a court trip to Dallas.
We had to go to Dallas.
And when the game was over, I was wandering the streets of Dallas all by myself and it was
as lonesome as I have been, except one other time I remember.
When I lived on the poultry farm, I stayed there on Thanksgiving so everybody else could live.
And the Mexicans were cleaning up the pasture back of the dairy farm, and those Mexicans would sing at night, and I couldn't understand a word, but they really sang very well.
And I'd get so homesick that it is,
It is really hard to hang around any longer.
On that Dallas trip, you were lonesome because you were by yourself?
That's right.
What about a court trip to Austin?
What was that like?
Well, after the game, I caught a ride with friends of mine that were coming to Moody's.
And I rode the Moody one Thanksgiving day from Austin Courtship in the rumble seat of a Model A Ford, I guess.
And I had a blanket to keep the wind and rain off of me.
Did any of your friends have a car?
No.
Let's see, who was the president when you were an undergraduate, A&M president?
T.O.
Walton.
I had trouble getting that name.
Describe him as you students thought of him.
Well, my personal opinion was that he did a great job.
And the fact that he was fired...
because he couldn't run the college after he'd been there 24 years or some such figure.
I don't know how long it was.
But it offended me to say that, well, he can't run this college after he'd been there plenty of years.
I had no personal contact with him at any time.
Did you all see him very often?
Not particularly.
I didn't have any reason to see him.
I didn't give him any reason to want to see me.
The depression effects continued all the years while you were a student.
Where did a student go if he was broke?
Was there any place he could go to get some financial help?
Well,
The last year that I was in A&M, I was living in the dormitory, and I got a loan from the former students, $400.
And the pay from the Army and the pay from the mess hall and the $400 I borrowed took care of my senior year.
But I still didn't have enough money to buy a senior ring.
And I got it in 1944.
My kids got to have a senior ring the first day they qualified for it, grandkids.
So that you didn't have a senior ring for ten years?
Eight years.
Eight years.
Nine years, maybe.
Since you have had that ring, are there any Aggie ring stories?
Did you ever lose it or somebody notice it in a special place?
Now then, when I taught at A&M, the students would see that ring, and they knew what it was.
And the other thing is that this design was adopted in 1935, my class, and it's been the same since 1935.
And the other thing was the watch that were awarded to outstanding teachers,
You told me that you got yours in 64.
Yes, sir.
I got mine in 65.
And to one extent or another, mine won't keep time now because I don't move around enough.
You've got to shake your hand and it'll run perfectly.
until about time you get in bed and then it stops and you have to set it every morning so I don't wear it anymore.
Religious emphasis week, describe what that was like when you were a student.
Well,
The date was set on 11 o'clock on Tuesday for a general convention.
And then leaders from the different religious groups would come there in addition to the main speaker.
And they would come there and would hold counseling sessions with the boys in the dormitory or in the YMCA or something like that.
And...
I didn't have any contact with them.
I'm not sure that I even remember religious emphasis week as a student.
I do as a faculty member.
Guyon Hall was a key place for big events of movies and speakers and so forth, is that right?
Right.
Do you remember any famous people that came to the campus during your student years?
Not really.
Because President Roosevelt didn't come during those years, I don't think.
That's right.
Now then, after I was a staff member, I remember all of the famous people that were there.
We'll get to those in a little bit.
In Sabeasa in those days, they had the big dances and the parties, the cotton ball and all that.
Right.
What did you folks who worked in the dining hall, what arrangements did you all have to make to get ready for those?
None.
None?
Okay.
So that didn't... That didn't enter into our job in the mess hall.
Let's see.
How did an Aggie get a date in those days?
There weren't any girls attending.
He couldn't get a date at home because mothers of high school girls didn't want to have a college boy going with their daughter.
So I didn't have a date.
You didn't have dates all those years?
That's right.
Did you go to the movie much?
After I moved in closer to the campus, I'd go once a month or something like that.
Where?
At the... Campus theater?
Campus.
No, not the campus theater.
Or downtown?
Oh, well, on the street there where Lupo's was.
Oh, okay.
See, there was a movie theater there, and it was just a few blocks from where I lived in the Ruffkin house.
What else was there at the Northgate?
What businesses and...
Well, Lupo's had a business there.
There's a barber shop, maybe two or three bookstores other than Northgate, restaurants or two.
That was about all.
Describe J.E.
Lupo and his business.
Well, Lupo was of a kind that they don't make anymore.
And my experience with Lupo mostly came about because his son was in my boy scout troop when I was a scoutmaster.
And I understand he had a file of old quizzes on genetics that he let people see it from time to time.
It didn't bother me that he did.
Now, I always understood that if a student was broke, Lupo would lend them money or would let them buy books on credit.
Did any of your buddies ever... Not that I know of.
When you were a student, what off-campus events do you remember?
You remember hearing some important things happening...
somewhere else that you heard on the radio or heard about?
Well, I was in the Camp Bullish in San Antonio when the downed quintuplets were born.
You know, I don't... That was after my junior year.
And let's see, President Roosevelt was...
in office during your student days, most of the time, wasn't he?
Yeah, he was.
And he had a son on the board of directors at A&M, Elliot.
And Elliot got money to build dormitory rooms, and that's when they cut out the project houses.
So he helped to get the money for the, what you and I call the new dorm area?
Right.
Really?
That's right.
There's no question.

where did elliott live in those years fort worth as far as i know okay uh... and so it just happened that a democratic governor appointed uh... the son of the president that's right to the a m board board of regents did uh... at uh... final review and other things like that did uh... the board were they there as far as you knew i didn't know
Did you and your buddies ever go into the steam tunnels?
I didn't.
No, I don't know of anybody else that did.
Did you ever hear of the secret fraternities in those days, the secret Aggie fraternities?
No, I did not know anything about it.
But were you aware that they existed?
Not really.
What the student indulgence is at that time?
Students drank beer.
What were the most popular varieties of beer?
How would I know if I never drank a bottle of beer?
But you didn't hear him talk about it?
Not any.
What about smoking?
Who smoked?
Did the typical student smoke?
Probably.
And were they smoking cigarettes or cigars or pipes?
They were smoking cigarettes, and most of us rolled our own.
Bull Durham.
Bull Durham?
Yes, sir.
And did you carry them in your shirt pocket?
Probably.
Where did the students smoke?
In their rooms?
Yeah, in their rooms.
But never in class, never in the buildings.
I don't know that for sure.
I never saw any smoking in class.
You said you never went to Hardlickers.
Were there any other places that were kind of off limits for you and your friends?
Not that I knew of.
Let's see.
On a home football day, describe...
a home football Saturday.
What time did y'all get up and what did you do?
On the home football game when I was a student at A&M, I'd get up in the morning and work.
At noon, I'd go over and wait for them to open the gate so I could get in free at Taft.
I really did not buy.
And I saw many A&M games when I was a faculty member because the Boy Scouts would serve as ushers.
So the Boy Scouts, of course I bought season tickets for a while.
I had an interesting experience.
We'll leave at 11.30 to go eat.
Gene Stallings was
well known to me when he was a student.
And when he was coach, he took two members of the faculty with him whenever he went to a ball game.
And so he took me and an English teacher to LSU when they played LSU.
And I enjoyed being with the team and so forth.
When halftime came, we had sideline passes.
When I said to Gene, well, you want me to go to the locker room with you?
And he said, yes, I do.
He said, when we puke, I want you to puke.
Gene's wife taught in college.
A&M the year before they were married.
My daughter was in her Sunday school class, so we knew her real well.
Fine people, fine people.
You bet.
Let's see.
How did you and your buddies learn the Aggie yells and songs?
I don't know that we all knew them.
I guess I went to Yale practice after I lived in the dormitory, but I did not go until I lived one year in the dormitory.
Let's see.
Describe, as a student, describe a final review.
Where was it held?
What did you and your buddies?
It was on the drill field in front of the Memorial Student Center.
Now, wait a minute.
I don't know when the Memorial Student Center was on that drill field anyway.
Was that a serious event for you and your buddies?
It wasn't for me.
And then commencement.
Where was commencement held?
Oh, wait a minute.
The awarding of degree, no, yeah, was held in the stadium on the south end.
And I have no idea who the speaker was that day, but when he got up, he
said, I want to congratulate the people of A&M, said, I've been standing here looking at the sun.
And I was introduced just as the sun went down over that stadium wall.
When you graduated, who came from your family?
My mother.
And she was the only one.
My father's brother was buried the day I graduated from A&M, and my sister was a
student in the TWU then.
She couldn't.
Do you remember going to silver taps as a student?
Yeah, I do.
Describe that.
Well, the people would gather on the campus and it was a very solemn occasion and it was a silence that
you could cut with a stick.
And that was the whole thing, so far as I know.
It was just playing of taps, and everybody gathered, and when the ceremony was over, they left.
Did it touch your hearts?
I really don't remember that it had much significance to me as a 17-year-old boy.
But did you all ever act silly during Muster?
Not that I know of.
Nobody's ever indicated to me that they did.
What about Muster?
Do you remember going to Aggie Muster before World War II?
I went to an Aggie Muster during World War II.
But what about before?
Well, now, look, I didn't go before.
Well...
I have the theory that World War II is really the birth of Aggie musters.
That's right.
You said you attended one during the war.
Describe that, please.
I got into O-RAN in North Africa sometime in the first part of April.
Of 43?
Four, okay.
And the...
group that I was with was a special group, 250 field grade officers going to a specific mission.
And we were there for about six weeks.
And I heard about the Aggie Muster and I went to the Aggie Muster in O-Ran and at the same time they had the Muster on Corregidor.
And I ran into a man not too long ago who was
invited to come to A&M because he was in the Aggie Muster and O-Ran, and I hadn't been invited to A&M because I did.
But I would have gone to the Aggie Muster in 45, had all my plans, but I was given orders to move out.
And where I went, the muster was me.
All right, this muster in Oran, how many people were there?
About 20.
And describe the content.
What did you all do?
Well, as far as I know, there wasn't much of a program.
We just met and said, here's a muster.
And I don't recall the...
any part of it except I know I went.
Do you remember any feelings you had?
No, I don't have any feelings.
I attended every muster when I was at A&M after I got home.
I'm making, I believe, my 24th muster speech this spring.
I'm doing the one in Albuquerque.
I did Nashville, Tennessee last year.
What was Aggie Bonfire like when you were a student?
Trash.
Did you help gather it?
No, I didn't.
Where was it held?
On the drill field.
And where'd that trash come from?
Well, just wherever the Aggies could find it.
And what did they put up on top of the bonfire?
Well, they had the T.U.
Dormitory up there.
Where did they get those, those privies?
As far as I know, they steal them wherever they can find them.
Who came to the bonfire when it was ignited, when it burned?
Who was there?
It wasn't the same at all when I was a student.
What are the experiences that build Aggie spirit and Aggie pride?
Well, I don't really know, I must admit, the companionship of other people in a common endeavor, I guess.
There's a statement that if you have it, you don't know where you got it, and if you don't have it, you can't understand it.
So I
I have that sort of feeling that I just have been acquainted with A&M so long.
Is it partly that A&M is inclusive, that it doesn't matter whether you're rich or poor, whether you're from the country or the city, if you'll do your share, you're welcome?
Is that part of it?
Part of it.
When you were a student, do you remember some poor boys and rich boys being friends?
No, I don't really, because we were all poor boys in this project house, or we wouldn't have been there.
And you know, the interesting thing to me is the fact that I started in 1968, maybe,
going to the former students with these cards and pulling out the ones who graduated.
And one of them was the man that the College of Engineering is named for.
H.B.
Zachary?
No.
Oh.
Look.
Oh, oh, oh, yeah, Dwight Look.
Dwight Look.
And some of the people in the project houses there
sort of felt like that that he wasn't exactly uh...
I don't know, it wasn't exactly uh...
I don't know what to say.
Did he live in a project house?
Yes, sir.
Where was he from?
I have no idea.
So he's a poor boy who made good financially.
Yes, sir, but
Let's keep it.
Yeah.
Talking about looking at what makes this Aggie feeling.
You had some friends who were, there was a variety of where they came from.
Right.
A variety of where they worshipped.
Right.
Were there some Hispanic students at A&M when you were?
Not any as far as I know.
What about Jewish?
They had a few.
And were they accepted?
I couldn't.
There was a Jewish boy on the table that I waited on that I didn't see that there was any discrimination at all.
What about, were there students from other countries?
Maybe from Cuba.
In Mexico, that's all I knew.
And they were accepted?
They were accepted.
They were not discriminated against.
And I'm guessing that during that period, one of the most common threads would have been that everybody was short on money.
That's true.
What are the qualities of being an Aggie?
What is an Aggie?
Since I'm not really a gung-ho Aggie, I don't really know how to answer that question.
But you're a very proud Aggie.
That's true.
But in the meantime, what I have done, and I consider that I've had a fantastic life, I'll tell you that.
had nothing to do with my student days at A&M.
I just went to A&M and worked hard and got by.
And when I graduated, I got a little tube, didn't have anything in it.
I wasn't old enough to be an officer.
And when I got my commission on my 21st birthday, I went to military camp for two weeks, and then I didn't have any further military experience until I was called into war.
Your first job after graduation was what?
Teaching.
Where?
St. Gabriel, Texas.
How did you get that job?
Well, the people would
that needed an ag teacher would come to College Station and look at the resumes of all of the ag ed majors, and they'd pick out three.
And when they picked out three, then they would arrange for us to come to be interviewed.
And 10 times I went, and Dick Burleson went,
And somebody else went.
And after five times of going, the students said, look, if you want a job, just go with Burleson and McNeil.
Because I was 20 years old at the time and looked like I was going on 18.
And there wasn't anybody that was going to hire an 18-year-old to teach vocational agriculture.
And I got to San Gabriel.
and I went back to A&M three weeks for a meets course so I could find out and the only lead they had was San Gabriel that I could go after I left finally.
I went to San Gabriel and they said now look you can't have the job if Jamie Clark doesn't give it to you but you just as well visit some of the others and so
When Jamie Clark came in and I said, look, Mr. Clark, I'm here to see about the job as ag teacher.
And he said, you've got the job.
Evidently, he may have talked to somebody else.
But I said, well, what do you pay?
I pay $90 a month.
I said, look, he said, we pay our superintendent $125 a month.
We're not going to pay the ag teacher more than the superintendent.
And it took me two months to get him to get the board to give me expenses as well as my $90 a month.
I got $75 for car expenses.
And that's my first job.
Now, San Gabriel is down south of?
West of, it's in Milam County.
Milam County.
Between Cameron and Rockdale.
About how big school was it then?
Oh, they had 25 or 30.
In the whole?
In the whole school.
In the whole school.
And your duty was to teach what?
Vocational agriculture half the time and teach some other class half of the time.
How well prepared did you feel A&M had made you for that task?
Not really.
Is that right?
That's right.
What did you feel A&M had left out?
Well, I didn't really get enough how to teach, enough experience.
I had one day in an education class that I had that I went out to practice teach, and one day of something else.
And so it was...
as good as anybody else was doing in any school as far as I was concerned, but it wasn't that comprehensive.
What time is it?
We've got about, it's now 1120.
Okay.
And we're about through with this tape, so that'll break out even.
As you look back, what effect has it had on your life that you went to Texas A&M?
It just kept me from being a renter on a cotton farm at Moody.
And some people that helped you get there and stay there must have earned gratitude from you.
Who are those people that you now feel most grateful to?
Well, both my daddy and mother.
And I'm grateful to the faculty that permitted the beginning of the project houses.
And as far as I'm concerned, the people that I dealt with in the project houses.
What did you... Now, we're using the word learn in a very broad sense.
What did you learn at A&M?
Not book learning, but...
I don't really know that I can answer that.
You learned to continue working hard because you had to.
That's right.
And I learned to get along in my classwork.
Mm-hmm.
do my work, except at the English course that I ignored.
What feelings do you hold in your heart now for Texas A&M?
Well, I'll tell you.
I'm very grateful to A&M because everything that I have been involved with includes A&M.
I also feel like
that A&M owes me more than I owe A&M in that I underwent bad treatment to get a degree from A&M.
And I did a better job of their overseas mission than anybody that went into that group.
I had contact with people of importance that I could sway in East Pakistan when I was there.
And the head of the party would come to me and ask me to do this or that or the other instead of them doing that job.
But I did a great job.
My family and I did.
